<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-20T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="920" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d920">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.0146/601: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-20T20:00:00+00:00">December 20, 1937—8
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 20—3:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>790. Your 498, December 19, 3 p.m., was conveyed to Cadogan this
                                afternoon. He thanked me for the information and said that no moving
                                of British troops in the Shanghai area were contemplated at present.
                                He said further that the Foreign Office would be very glad to
                                exchange views and advance information with respect to any future
                                reduction.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>